      <TR VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
        <TD HEIGHT=141 COLSPAN=5>
        </TD>
        <TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH=693 HEIGHT=133 COLSPAN=3>
                    
                      <div align="left">
                      <table border="0" width="696" height="136">
                        <tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> 2000-06-15 - PC Gamer talks about EverQuest</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19'></td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#C0C0C0> <p>The <b>July 2000</b> issues of <b>PC Gamer</b> includes an interview on
EverQuest and the Kunark expansion. Entitled &quot;EverQuest Woes? Success
always comes with some strings attached&quot; the article includes an interview
with Brad McQuaid executive producer of EverQuest. Here are some excerpts:</p>
<p>Brad answers the question of Verant customer support. PC Gamer asks
&quot;..some EverQuest players are alleging that Verant is playing little or no
attention to discussion boards that deal with complaints about EverQuest, is
that true....&quot; Brad replies.. &quot;Definitely not true...&quot; I wonder
is all of you would agree. Brad points at the large player base of EQ as proof
that the game delivers what the audience (i.e. us) wants. I would agree, I have
also seen more complaints concerning this game then almost any other, including
Ultima Online!</p>
<p>Brad answers a question concerning overall player satisfaction with the game.
&quot;I think we can be fairly certain they are very satisfied.....&quot; I
wonder is you agree, we would love to get your feedback, post your thoughts in
our forum.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Brad answers a question on overcrowding. &quot;In the last six months we have
been a victim of our own success... Bottom line, servers have more players at
peak hours then we would like. He goes on to say that Verant plans to revamp
zones to spread players out as well as add new zones, although no specifics
where given.</p>
<p>Brad talks about &quot;play nice&quot; and selling EQ items in the
&quot;real&quot; world. &quot;...we feel that based on polls as well as general
feedback, that the &quot;play nice&quot; rules are wanted by our player base.
Are they perfect, heck no, and rules in a game like this will continue to evolve
and adapt.&quot;&nbsp; On selling EQ items Brad replies &quot;It is my
understanding that we will make additional efforts in the future to curb these
auctions...&quot; Not sure why the fokes at Verant care that people sell game
items, but they do seem to be against the idea.</p>
<p>Brad talks about the future of EQ. &quot;More content and better refinement
of rules and game mechanics. Id love to see a second expansion, and If love to
see a sequel one day. Verants and Sony Onlines vision for EQ goes pretty far
into the future and we are definitely considering EQ as a franchise as opposed
to a single game, And based on EQs huge success thus far, I think the future is
pretty bright.&quot; We certainly hope so! A franchise of EverQuest like games, perhaps
a sequel - goes pretty good to us. </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='55' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> Source: PC Gamer -  </font> <a href=http://www.pcgamer.com </a> www.pcgamer.com </td></tr>    
